Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Cheaper Gas May Fuel Growth
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Cheaper Gas May Fuel Growth

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Falling gas prices as stimulus. A steady decline in gasoline prices are providing a glimmer of good news amid all the weak economic data recently -- and offering some hope of reviving those economic measures. The average price of regular gasoline has dropped to $3.790 a gallon --  down 3.8% from the 2012 peak of $3.941 reached April 2. Gas prices impact just about every aspect of the economy, so a pullback provides a form of stimulus, the WSJ notes in this A1 story. The U.S. Energy Information Administration estimates that a 10-cent drop in pump prices can add roughly 0.1% to disposable household income. Of course, prices are still near record highs and the downside to all this is that part of the reason for the drop is economic softness in the U.S. and Europe.
THE DAY AHEAD:
Walt Disney is expected to post solid results after markets close. Its parks and resorts should be able to outweigh some of the damage the box-office flop "John Carter" inflicted on its film studio. The economic agenda is pretty light – the NFIB Small Business survey is seen improving slightly in April.
On Capitol Hill, a Ron Paul-led House Financial Services subcommittee looks at some pending legislation to reform the Fed – none of these proposed laws have much chance of going anywhere. And the Senate Finance Committee vets some Obama nominees  -- two for Treasury Dept. jobs and one for the U.S. International Trade Commission.

Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Will Inflation Kill QE3 Hopes?

PARAGRAPH.#text:
THE DAY AHEAD: Hopes for an economy-boosting third round of quantitative easing have been growing since last week's jobs report, but inflation has to stay subdued for the Fed to pull the trigger on more bond buying. That's why today's PPI numbers and tomorrow's CPI data are being watched so closely. Economists expect a jump in energy costs will push March's producer-price index to 3.4% -- up a bit from February, but half of September's pace, says Ahead of the Tape's Spencer Jakab.
The other piece of data to watch is weekly jobless claims, which are  expected to inch up slightly to 358,000. Fed Vice Chairwoman Janet Yellen warned last night that "labor market slack will remain substantial for a number of years to come." And she said that more easing "could be warranted if the recovery proceeds at a slower-than-expected pace," the Journal's Jon Hilsenrath reports.
Also today, Google is expected to report solid earnings growth after markets close. Investors will be focused on cost-per-click declines – the shift to mobile searches could take a toll on prices paid for Google's online advertising.

Headlines.Headline: SEC's New Bounties Could Disrupt Corporate-Compliance Efforts

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Monday.) WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--An in-house lawyer interviews an employee about suspected wrongdoing at the company. PARAGRAPH.#text: WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--U.S. lawmakers could soon replace feisty rhetoric with action on China and its currency policy. Frustrated members of Congress may vote in the coming weeks on legislation penalizing Chinese imports for Beijing's artificially low currency. PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Disappointing U.S. economic data Wednesday put a damper on investor optimism on the pace of the recovery. An unexpected drop in the Chicago Purchasing Managers' business-activity index - to 46.1 from an expected 52.0 - sparked concerns that the Institute for Supply Management's manufacturing report Thursday may also reflect weakness. "Investors were shaken by the [Chicago] data release, which bodes ill for the main event [Thursday]," wrote Gavan Nolan, Markit's vice president, credit research.

"Key economic indicators suggest orders, manufacturing and construction activity decreased in the second quarter, but the pace of decline slowed," said S&P credit analyst Dan Picciotto.
